+### Bash regex `=~` no `{N,M}` repetition (canonical two-check form)
+
+Bash's `[[ … =~ … ]]` operator uses POSIX ERE, which **does not** support
+the `{N,M}` repetition quantifier. A `validate <subject>` arm whose input
+has both a length-range constraint AND a character-class constraint cannot
+encode both inside one regex:
+
+```bash
+# FORBIDDEN — bash =~ does NOT support {N,M}; runtime error: bash: invalid repetition count(s)
+if [[ "$arg" =~ ^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]{4,256}$ ]]; then …
+
+# CANONICAL — split the length gate from the char-class regex
+local len="${#arg}"
+if (( len >= 4 && len <= 256 )) && [[ "$arg" =~ ^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]+$ ]]; then
+  # ok envelope
+  jq -nc --arg v "$arg" '{status:"ok", value:$v}'
+else
+  # reject envelope — include observed_length so callers see WHY
+  jq -nc --arg v "$arg" --argjson len "$len" \
+    '{status:"reject", value:$v, reason:"pattern_or_length_mismatch",
+      pattern:"^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]+$", length_range:"[4, 256]",
+      observed_length:$len}'
+fi
+```
+
+**Why operators step on this trap:**
+
+- Failure is RUNTIME (`bash: invalid repetition count(s)`), not parse-time.
+  `bash -n script.sh` passes; the broken arm only blows up when a value
+  reaches it. Test coverage that omits the validate path ships the bug.
+- PCRE, `grep -P`, Python `re`, JavaScript regex, and Rust `regex` crate
+  all support `{N,M}` — operators coming from those languages assume bash
+  does too.
+- `[[:digit:]]{N,M}` looks identical to a POSIX character class with
+  repetition; it's not. Bash's ERE has POSIX bracket classes (the
+  `[[:digit:]]` part), but no `{N,M}` quantifier.
 
+**Canonical reject envelope shape** (mirrors `idempotency-replay-guard.sh:280`
+production use):
+
+```json
+{
+  "schema_version": "<surface>.v1",
+  "command": "validate",
+  "subject": "<subject>",
+  "ts": "<iso>",
+  "status": "reject",
+  "value": "<received>",
+  "reason": "pattern_or_length_mismatch",
+  "pattern": "^[A-Za-z0-9._/#:-]+$",
+  "length_range": "[4, 256]",
+  "observed_length": <int>
+}
+```
+
+The `observed_length` field is mandatory — without it, an operator
+debugging a rejected value can't tell whether the failure was length-side
+or char-class-side.
